WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.610 --> 00:00:04.220
The year is 1968. We're at the Olympic Games in

2
00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:08.540
Mexico City. Dick Fosbury has just made a record-breaking high

3
00:00:08.580 --> 00:00:11.900
jump, winning the gold medal and completely changing how future

4
00:00:11.980 --> 00:00:15.780
athletes approach the high jump. But let's rewind and see

5
00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:19.600
how critical thinking played a part in getting Fosbury here.

6
00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:23.040
For years, high jumpers used a variety of techniques, all

7
00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:25.020
of which allowed for the jumper to land on their

8
00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:28.560
feet after clearing the bar. Athletes assumed that these were

9
00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:32.420
the most optimal methods. But in high school, Fosbury tried

10
00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:36.520
them and found himself getting below average results. So he

11
00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:40.460
asked himself, "Hmm, how else could I jump over this

12
00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:44.820
bar?" Instead of accepting the norm, he began experimenting and

13
00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:47.560
came up with a new and different jumping method. He

14
00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:49.980
would jump and rotate in the air so that he

15
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.340
went over the bar headfirst on his back. At the

16
00:00:53.380 --> 00:00:55.820
time, he was laughed at and criticized for this new

17
00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:58.910
method. It looked pretty silly and was so different from

18
00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:02.500
the typical methods, but it worked due to some unexpected

19
00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:07.160
benefits. It lowered Fosbury's center of gravity, actually placing it

20
00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:10.140
below the bar even though he himself was jumping over

21
00:01:10.180 --> 00:01:13.800
it. This allowed him to use less energy while increasing

22
00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:17.450
his height. And by leaping backwards, he was reducing his

23
00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:19.700
chances of knocking the bar off with his arms and

24
00:01:19.740 --> 00:01:24.190
legs. Using this technique, Fosbury was jumping higher than anyone

25
00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:27.060
else on his high school track team. He continued to

26
00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:29.720
hone this method in college and moved on to qualify

27
00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:33.480
for the Olympics. And so here we are, back in

28
00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:38.480
1968, with Fosbury winning the Olympic gold medal. He took

29
00:01:38.520 --> 00:01:41.960
a problem, not being able to jump particularly high, and

30
00:01:42.020 --> 00:01:44.740
used critical thinking to come up with a solution, a

31
00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:48.240
new way of jumping that greatly improved his results. To

32
00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:51.680
this day, almost every high jumper uses this method, now

33
00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:55.070
known as the Fosbury Flop. And so it just goes

34
00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:58.320
to show how critical thinking can both raise the bar

35
00:01:58.360 --> 00:01:59.400
and change the game.

36
